<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-589-947  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 589 947.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 19 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>US agents arrest alleged thief of telephone credit cards. (JohnFarrell, member of 'Paradox' software piracy ring arrested in NewYork state)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telecommunications ServicesTelephone systemsComputer HackersCredit AuthorizationComputer CrimesFraudLaw Enforcement.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>US AGENTS ARREST ALLEGED THIEF OF TELEPHONE CREDIT CARDS BETHPAGE, NEW YORK,U.S.A.,1990 OCT 19 (NB) -- New York State Police, acting in concert withthree other law enforcement agencies, have executed a search warrant inBethpage, Long Island and arrested 17 year-old John Farrell who, through theuse of computer algorithms, allegedly bilked telephone companies in excess of$1 million.andM;In conjunction with the execution of the warrant, Major Timothy M. Rabbett ofthe NY State Police released a statement saying that Farrell had usedcomputer programs to acquire over 100 valid telephone credit card numbers andhad then used these numbers over 500 times.andP;  He said the credit card numberswere then posted on computer bulletin boards throughout the US, England,Australia, Germany and Denmark.andM;New York State Police Special Investigator Donald Delaney, who led thearresting team, told Newsbytes that, in the course of the execution of thesearch warrant at 83 South 3rd Street in Bethpage, Long Island, a CommodoreAmiga and a large number of floppy disks were impounded.andP;  Delaney said&quot;Farrell, who operated under the handle &quot;Rokman,&quot; is a member of a groupcalled 'Paradox' which pirates software as soon as it is released anddistributes it to its members.andP;  Paradox's members are located, among otherplaces, in Long Island, Chicago, France and Denmark.andP;  Farrell was using thestolen credit card numbers for communications with other Paradox members.&quot;andO;Delaney added that Farrell had admitted obtaining and using the credit cardnumbers.andM;Delaney also said, &quot;With the new technology that has been developed,telephone carriers can easily detect where these credit card calls are beingmade from and monitor the number making the calls.andP;  This information can thenbe passed on to the appropriate law enforcement agency for action.andP;  It seemsfoolish for people to continue activities like these.&quot;andM;Other police agencies assisting in the investigation are the US SecretService, the Nassau County, New York District Attorney's office, and theSuffolk County, New York District Attorney's office.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/199010019)</TEXT></DOC>